04473nam a22005415i 9780226360874DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20092009ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802263608747 a10.7208/97802263608742doi  a(DE-B1597)523150  a(OCoLC)1135569517  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL 4aHD7288.78.U52bC45 2010 7aSOC0000002bisacsh04a363.58509773112221 aHunt, D. Bradford, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aBlueprint for Disaster :bThe Unraveling of Chicago Public Housing /cD. Bradford Hunt. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2009] 4c©2009  a1 online resource (392 p.) :b28 halftones, 4 line drawings, 1 table  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aHistorical Studies of Urban America00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tILLUSTRATIONS -- tIntroduction: What Went Wrong with Public Housing in Chicago? -- t1. The 1937 Housing Act Revisited -- t2. Building the Chicago Housing Authority -- t3. Clearing Chicago’s Slums -- t4. The End of Integration and the Taming of the CHA -- t5. Designing High- Rise Disasters -- t6. Planning a Social Disaster -- t7. The Loss of the Working Class -- t8. The Tenants Revolt -- t9. The Gautreaux Case and the Limits of Judicial Activism -- t10. The Long Road to Rebirth -- tConclusion: The Unraveling of Chicago Public Housing -- tAcknowledgments -- tA Note on Sources -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aNow considered a dysfunctional mess, Chicago’s public housing projects once had long waiting lists of would-be residents hoping to leave the slums behind. So what went wrong? To answer this complicated question, D. Bradford Hunt traces public housing’s history in Chicago from its New Deal roots through current mayor Richard M. Daley’s Plan for Transformation. In the process, he chronicles the Chicago Housing Authority’s own transformation from the city’s most progressive government agency to its largest slumlord. Challenging explanations that attribute the projects’ decline primarily to racial discrimination and real estate interests, Hunt argues that well-intentioned but misguided policy decisions—ranging from design choices to maintenance contracts—also paved the road to failure. Moreover, administrators who fully understood the potential drawbacks did not try to halt such deeply flawed projects as Cabrini-Green and the Robert Taylor Homes. These massive high-rise complexes housed unprecedented numbers of children but relatively few adults, engendering disorder that pushed out the working class and, consequently, the rents needed to maintain the buildings. The resulting combination of fiscal crisis, managerial incompetence, and social unrest plunged the CHA into a quagmire from which it is still struggling to emerge. Blueprint for Disaster, then,is an urgent reminder of the havoc poorly conceived policy can wreak on our most vulnerable citizens.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aPublic housingxHistoryx20th centuryxIllinoisxChicago. 0aPublic housingzIllinoiszChicagoxHistoryy20th century. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG and UP eBook Package 2000-2015z978311063872108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311063538640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226360874423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780226360874.jpg  a978-3-11-063538-6  University of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  a978-3-11-063872-1  DG and UP eBook Package 2000-2015c2000d2015  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles